  "text": "## Rate Limiting Middleware Patterns Across Envoy and Kubernetes\n\n### Envoy (envoyproxy/envoy) - C++ Implementation\n\nEnvoy implements rate limiting through two primary mechanisms:\n\n#### 1. Global Rate Limit Service Client (gRPC-based)\nThe global rate limiting is implemented in `source/extensions/filters/common/ratelimit/ratelimit_impl.h/cc`. The key class is `GrpcClientImpl` which:\n- Implements the `Client` interface and `RateLimitAsyncCallbacks` from the gRPC async client framework\n- Uses `envoy::service::ratelimit::v3::RateLimitService` protocol buffer definition\n- The `limit()` method (line 76-93 in ratelimit_impl.cc) constructs a `RateLimitRequest`, sends it asynchronously via `async_client_->send()`, and handles responses through `onSuccess()` and `onFailure()` callbacks\n- The `createRequest()` static method builds descriptors and descriptor entries from request parameters, allowing fine-grained rate limit definitions\n- Supports timeout configuration and parent span tracing for distributed tracing integration\n\nThe HTTP rate limit filter at `source/extensions/filters/http/ratelimit/ratelimit.h/cc` uses this client to make decisions on whether to allow or reject requests. Network and listener filters follow similar patterns with their own implementations.\n\n#### 2. Local Rate Limit Filter (Token Bucket-based)\nLocal rate limiting is implemented in `source/extensions/filters/common/local_ratelimit/local_ratelimit_impl.h/cc`. This includes:\n- `LocalRateLimiterImpl`: The main rate limiter implementing the local rate limiting logic\n- `RateLimitTokenBucket`: Token bucket implementation for rate limiting\n- `DynamicDescriptor`: Manages dynamic descriptors with LRU-based eviction for descriptor limits\n- `DynamicDescriptorMap`: Maps user-configured descriptors to dynamic token buckets\n- Uses `source/common/common/token_bucket_impl.h/cc` which provides the underlying `TokenBucketImpl` class\n\nThe token bucket pattern allows for smooth rate limiting with configurable fill rates (tokens per unit time) and maximum token capacity. Dynamic descriptors enable hierarchical rate limiting based on request characteristics.\n\nProtocol buffer definitions for rate limiting are in:\n- `api/envoy/service/ratelimit/v3/rls.proto`: Service definition\n- `api/envoy/extensions/common/ratelimit/v3/ratelimit.proto`: Common message definitions\n- `api/envoy/config/ratelimit/v3/rls.proto`: Configuration schema\n- `api/envoy/type/v3/token_bucket.proto`: Token bucket parameters\n\n### Kubernetes (kubernetes/kubernetes) - Go Implementation\n\nKubernetes implements Advanced Priority and Fairness (APF) system, a sophisticated rate limiting and request prioritization mechanism:\n\n#### 1. APF Filter and Controller Architecture\nThe main entry points are:\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/util/flowcontrol/apf_filter.go`: Defines the `Interface` with the `Handle()` method that requests must pass through\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/util/flowcontrol/apf_controller.go`: Implements the controller that manages priority level configurations (PriorityLevelConfiguration and FlowSchema objects) and adjusts concurrency limits\n- The controller implements seat borrowing (periodic adjustment of CurrentCLs across priority levels) with 10-second adjustment periods\n- Smoothed seat demand tracking uses exponential decay with a 5-minute half-life\n\n#### 2. Fair Queuing Implementation\nThe core fair queuing logic is in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/util/flowcontrol/fairqueuing/queueset/`:\n- `queueset.go`: Implements the `queueSet` type which manages fair queuing for server requests\n- Uses multiple FIFO queues organized by priority to prevent starvation\n- Implements virtual time-based dispatching to ensure fair resource allocation\n- `fifo_list.go`: Manages FIFO queue operations\n- `types.go`: Defines configuration and request structures\n- `eventclock/` packages provide timing abstractions for testing\n- `integrator.go`: Implements smoothing of seat demand figures\n\n#### 3. Work Estimation and Seat-based Rate Limiting\nKubernetes uses a \"seats\" concept to measure and limit request concurrency:\n- `request/width.go`: Defines `WorkEstimate` with `InitialSeats`, `FinalSeats`, and `AdditionalLatency`\n- `request/seat_seconds.go`: Implements `SeatSeconds` measurement using fixed-point arithmetic for work tracking\n- `request/list_work_estimator.go`: Estimates work for LIST operations based on object counts\n- `request/mutating_work_estimator.go`: Estimates work for mutating operations\n- `request/object_count_tracker.go`: Tracks object counts for accurate work estimation\n\n#### 4. Concurrency and Seat Allocation\nConcurrency allocation across priority levels:\n- `conc_alloc.go`: Implements the `computeConcurrencyAllocation()` algorithm that proportionally allocates seats based on priority level targets, with min/max bounds\n- `max_seats.go`: Implements `MaxSeatsTracker` interface managing per-priority-level seat limits\n- Priority levels can borrow seats from other underutilized priority levels\n\n#### 5. Priority Level Configuration\nConfiguration management:\n- `pkg/apis/flowcontrol/v1/defaults.go`: Default configurations for priority levels and flow schemas\n- `pkg/apis/flowcontrol/types.go`: API types for FlowSchema and PriorityLevelConfiguration\n- `pkg/apis/flowcontrol/util/helpers.go`: Utility functions for processing configurations\n\n#### 6. Supporting Infrastructure\n- `metrics/metrics.go`: Prometheus metrics for monitoring APF behavior (queue lengths, latencies, etc.)\n- `watch_tracker.go`: Tracks concurrent watch connections for fair queuing\n- `dropped_requests_tracker.go`: Records metrics for requests dropped due to rate limits\n- `rule.go`: Request classification rules for mapping requests to priority levels and flow schemas\n\n### Pattern Comparison\n\n**Envoy's approach** emphasizes simplicity and flexibility:\n- Local rate limiting uses straightforward token buckets\n- Global rate limiting delegates to an external RLS service via gRPC\n- Descriptors allow hierarchical, multi-dimensional rate limiting\n\n**Kubernetes's approach** emphasizes fairness and priority:\n- Fair queuing ensures no priority level starves others\n- Work estimation allows different request types to consume different amounts of concurrency\n- Seat borrowing dynamically redistributes capacity based on actual demand\n- Multiple layers (priority level → flow schema → request) provide fine-grained control\n\nBoth systems handle distributed, multi-stage request processing and provide monitoring/metrics integration."
